  "prompt": "Why is The Sandman called 'sandman'?",
  "response": "The Sandman's name comes from European folklore. The Sandman is a mythical figure who is said to sprinkle sand or dust into the eyes of children at night to bring on sleep and pleasant dreams.\n\nHere's a breakdown of why Neil Gaiman chose the name and how it connects to the character:\n\n*   **Folklore Connection:** Gaiman's Sandman, also known as Dream or Morpheus, is heavily influenced by this existing folklore figure. He's not *exactly* the same, but the connection is clear. His role is essentially to control dreams and guard the realm of sleep, which ties directly to the idea of someone bringing on sleep.\n\n*   **Evoking Mystery and Imagination:** The name \"The Sandman\" has a whimsical, magical quality that perfectly suits the fantastical nature of the comic series. It hints at the power and mystery surrounding the character.\n\n*   **Deconstruction of Myth:** Gaiman takes the familiar childhood myth of the Sandman and deconstructs it, exploring the darker and more complex aspects of dreams, nightmares, and the power of stories. He takes a simple concept and elevates it into a profound and multifaceted narrative.\n\nIn summary, the Sandman is called \"The Sandman\" because he is inspired by the traditional folklore figure associated with bringing sleep and dreams. Gaiman uses this familiar association to create a complex and powerful character who embodies the very essence of dreaming.",
